                                Image Upload Backend – Short Notes

Technologies used in the system:

Node.js – Runs JavaScript on the server
Express.js – Framework used to create API routes
Multer – Middleware used to handle file uploads
ImageKit – Cloud service used to store images
MongoDB – Database used to store post data


1. Purpose of the System
The system allows a user to upload an image with a caption.
The image is stored in cloud storage instead of the server.
Only the image URL and caption are stored in the database.
This makes the system faster and scalable.


2. User Request
The user selects an image file from the browser.
The user also enters a caption.
The browser sends this data to the backend through an HTTP POST request.
The request format is multipart/form-data because it contains a file.


3. Express Server Receives Request
The backend server built using Express.js receives the request.
The server route is responsible for creating a post.
Before processing the request, a middleware is used to handle the file.


4. File Processing Using Multer
Multer extracts the uploaded image from the request.
The uploaded file is stored temporarily in memory (RAM).
The file becomes available as file data inside the request object.
This data is stored as a buffer.


5. Buffer and Base64 Conversion
The image stored in memory is in binary format (buffer).
Cloud storage services usually require Base64 encoded data.
The buffer is converted into Base64 format.
Base64 allows binary files to be transmitted as text.


6. Uploading Image to Cloud Storage
The backend sends the image data to ImageKit.
ImageKit stores the image in its cloud storage.
The server authenticates using a private API key.
The image is uploaded with a specified file name.


7. ImageKit Response

After uploading the image, ImageKit returns a response containing:

Image metadata
File information
Public image URL

This URL is the most important part because it allows the image to be accessed from anywhere on the internet.

8. Saving Data in Database
After receiving the image URL, the backend stores the data in MongoDB.
A new post document is created in the database.
Each post contains:
Image URL
Caption

The database only stores text data, not the image itself.


9. Success Response
Once the post is saved in the database, the server sends a response.
The response confirms that the post was created successfully.
The response also returns the newly created post data.
10. Fetching Posts

The system also has another API to retrieve posts.

The backend queries MongoDB.
All stored posts are retrieved.
The posts are sent back to the client in JSON format.
The frontend displays the caption and loads the image using the stored URL.


11. Why This Architecture is Used

This system design has several advantages:

The server does not store heavy image files.
Images are delivered faster using a CDN.
The database remains lightweight.
The system can handle large numbers of users and images.


12. Complete Flow Summary
User uploads image and caption
Browser sends request to backend
Express server receives the request
Multer extracts the image file
Image stored temporarily in memory
File converted to Base64
Image uploaded to ImageKit cloud
ImageKit returns image URL
URL and caption stored in MongoDB
Server sends success response